  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>

        <div rend="parallel">
          <p xml:id="AN183.1-kilavi">talaimakaṉ kuṟitta paruvavaravukaṇṭu talaimaka ṭōḻikkuc colliyatu.</p>
          <p xml:lang="en">What SHE said to the confidante after seeing the arrival of the season indicated by HIM.</p>
        </div>
        <div rend="parallel">
      <lg xml:id="AN183.1">
        <l>kuvaḷai yuṇkaṇ kaluḻavun tiruntiḻait</l>
        <l>titalai yalku lavvari vāṭavu</l>
        <l>mattama raḻuva nattuṟan taruḷār</l>
        <l>ceṉṟucē ṇiṭaiya rāyiṉu naṉṟu</l>
        <l>nīṭala reṉṟi tōḻi pāṭāṉṟu</l>
        <l>paṉittuṟaip peruṅkaṭa liraintunīr parukik</l>
        <l>kuvavuttirai varuntaka koḷḷai cāṟṟiya, ku<supplied>ṭa</supplied>kkērpu</l>
        <l>vayavuppiṭi yiṉattiṉ vayiṉvayiṟ ṟōṉṟi</l>
        <l>yiruṅ<supplied>ki</supplied>ḷaik koṇmū voruṅkuṭaṉ ṟuvaṉṟik</l>
        <l>kālai vantaṉṟāṟ kārē mālaik</l>
        <l>kuḷirkoḷ piṭaviṉ kūrmukai yalari</l>
        <l>vaṇṭuvāy tiṟakkun taṇṭār nāṟṟaṅ</l>
        <l>kūti raccirat tūtai tūṟṟap</l>
        <l>paṉiyalaik kalakkiya neñcamoṭu</l>
        <l>varuntuva mallamō pirinticiṉōr tiṟattē.</l>
      </lg>
      <lg xml:lang="en">
        <l>He who was inconsiderate, abandoning us in the thicket full of thornapple trees, (3)</l>
        <l>although [my] waterlily kajal eyes were dimming and the pretty lines</l>
        <l>on my hips with perfect jewels [and] beauty spots were fading, (1f.)</l>
        <l>even though, having gone, he is in a distant place you may well</l>
        <l>say, friend, that he won’t delay. (4-5c)</l>
        <l>[Its] breadth increasing, roaring, drinking water from the vast ocean with chilly ghats, (5df.)</l>
        <l>rising to the west in order to duly proclaim the plunder that comes from the piling waves, (7)</l>
        <l>appearing in place after place like groups of strong elephant cows, (8)</l>
        <l>the clouds filling up together with [their] dark relatives, (9)</l>
        <l>the time has come indeed, the rainy season. In the evening, (10)</l>
        <l>as the cold wind of the cold dewy season spreads (13)</l>
        <l>the fragrance of cool garlands on which bees open the mouths (12)</l>
        <l>of the flowers with pointed buds of the cold Piṭavu, (11)</l>
        <l>with a heart that the dew harasses [and] stirs up, (14)</l>
        <l>we shall suffer, shall we not, on account of him who parted [from us]? (15)</l>
      </lg>
        </div>
    </body>
